</div><div class="info-panel__citations info-panel__item"><a href="#tab-citations" class="btn btn--inverse btn--slim" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="View Citations" aria-label="View Citations"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-format_quote"></i></a></div><div class="info-panel__formats info-panel__item"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access" data-toggle="tooltip" data-original-title="Go to purchase options" aria-label="Go to purchase options"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="link-text">Get Access</span></a></div></div></div></div></header><div data-core-nav="header" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-nav-wrapper core-container" aria-label="Article navigation"><div><button aria-controls="article_sections_menu" aria-expanded="false" aria-label="Toggle section navigation menu"><i class="icon-list" aria-hidden="true"></i><span>Contents</span></button><nav id="article_sections_menu" aria-label="Contents" data-core-nav="article"><ul><li><a href="#abstract">Abstract</a></li><li><a href="#core-sec-figures">Figures</a></li><li><a href="#bibliography">References</a></li></ul></nav></div><nav id="article_collateral_menu"><ul class="collateral-pill" data-core-nav="collateral"><li><a href="#core-collateral-info" aria-controls="core-collateral-info" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Information & Authors" title="Information & Authors" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-info"></i><span class="sr-only">Information & Authors</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-metrics" aria-controls="core-collateral-metrics" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Metrics & Citations" title="Metrics & Citations" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-metrics"></i><span class="sr-only">Metrics & Citations</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-controls="core-collateral-purchase-access" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Get Access" title="Get Access" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span class="sr-only">Get Access</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-references" aria-controls="core-collateral-references" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="References" title="References" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-references"></i><span class="sr-only">References</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-figures" aria-controls="core-collateral-figures" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Figures" title="Figures" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-photo"></i><span class="sr-only">Figures</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-tables" aria-controls="core-collateral-tables" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Tables" title="Tables" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-table"></i><span class="sr-only">Tables</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-media" aria-controls="core-collateral-media" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Media" title="Media" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-play-circle-filled"></i><span class="sr-only">Media</span></a></li><li><a href="#core-collateral-share" aria-controls="core-collateral-share" aria-disabled="true" disabled="true" data-toggle="tooltip" data-placement="left" data-original-title="Share" title="Share" aria-expanded="false"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-share"></i><span class="sr-only">Share</span></a></li></ul></nav></div></div><div data-core-wrapper="content"><div id="abstracts" data-extent="frontmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="abstract" property="abstract" typeof="Text" role="doc-abstract"><h2 property="name">Abstract</h2><div role="paragraph">The radiologic manifestations of cholangiocarcinomas are extremely diverse, since these tumors vary greatly in location, growth pattern, and histologic type. Familiarity with the imaging manifestations of cholangiocarcinomas is important for accurate detection and characterization of these tumors and assessment of resectability. Advances in imaging techniques have led to the availability of an array of modalities that, used independently or in combination, can aid in the accurate diagnosis and evaluation of cholangiocarcinomas in preparation for advanced surgical procedures and treatment planning. Response to novel targeted therapies can also be assessed with newer imaging tools. Hence, knowledge of current and emerging imaging applications is essential for correct diagnosis and appropriate management of these tumors.</div><div role="paragraph">© RSNA, 2008</div></section></div></div><section id="bodymatter" data-extent="bodymatter" property="articleBody" typeof="Text"><div class="core-container"><section aria-labelledby="denial-block-title" class="denial-block "><h2 id="denial-block-title" class="denial-block__title">Get full access to this article</h2><p class="denial-block__text">View all available purchase options and get full access to this article.</p><div class="denial-block__cta"><a href="#core-collateral-purchase-access" class="btn btn--access"><i aria-hidden="true" class="icon-lock-open"></i><span>Get Access</span></a></div><footer class="denial-block__footer"><span>Already a Subscriber? </span><span>Sign in as an </span><a href="/action/showLogin?redirectUri=/doi/10.1148/rg.285075183">individual</a><span> or via your </span><a href="/action/ssostart?uri=/doi/10.1148/rg.285075183">institution</a></footer></section></div></section><section id="backmatter" data-extent="backmatter"><div class="core-container"><section id="core-sec-figures" data-type="figures"><h2>Figures</h2><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F1" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19c01x.jpeg" height="966" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F1" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 1.</b>  Drawing illustrates the locations of the three types of cholangiocarcinomas: intrahepatic (peripheral) (yellow), perihilar (blue), and extrahepatic (orange).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F1">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F2" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19c02x.jpeg" height="454" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F2" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 2.</b>  Drawings illustrate the Bismuth-Corlette classification of perihilar cholangiocarcinomas. Type I involves the common hepatic duct (CHD); type II, the CHD and the junction of the RHD and LHD; type IIIA, the CHD, biliary junction, and RHD; type IIIB, the CHD, biliary junction, and LHD; and type IV, the CHD and the biliary junction, with extension to both the RHD and LHD or a multifocal bile duct tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F2">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g03a.jpeg" height="1548" width="1536" aria-labelledby="F3A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3a.</b>  Mass-forming peripheral cholangiocarcinomas. <b>(a)</b> Transabdominal US image obtained in a 73-year-old woman shows a hypoechoic lesion (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Transabdominal US image obtained in a 41-year-old man shows a hyperechoic lesion (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Transabdominal US image obtained in a 66-year-old woman shows a mixed-echogenicity lesion (arrowheads) with biliary dilatation (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F3A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g03b.jpeg" height="1512" width="1500" aria-labelledby="F3B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3b.</b>  Mass-forming peripheral cholangiocarcinomas. <b>(a)</b> Transabdominal US image obtained in a 73-year-old woman shows a hypoechoic lesion (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Transabdominal US image obtained in a 41-year-old man shows a hyperechoic lesion (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Transabdominal US image obtained in a 66-year-old woman shows a mixed-echogenicity lesion (arrowheads) with biliary dilatation (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F3B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F3C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g03c.jpeg" height="1548" width="1545" aria-labelledby="F3C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 3c.</b>  Mass-forming peripheral cholangiocarcinomas. <b>(a)</b> Transabdominal US image obtained in a 73-year-old woman shows a hypoechoic lesion (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Transabdominal US image obtained in a 41-year-old man shows a hyperechoic lesion (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Transabdominal US image obtained in a 66-year-old woman shows a mixed-echogenicity lesion (arrowheads) with biliary dilatation (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F3C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g04a.jpeg" height="1357" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4a.</b>  CT appearances of cholangiocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal reformatted CT image obtained in a 72-year-old woman shows an infiltrating intraductal extrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma causing irregular thickening and enhancement (white arrows) of the CBD with upstream dilatation of intrahepatic biliary radicles (black arrow). Inset shows a magnified view of the involved CBD (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Multidetector CT scan through the liver obtained in an 82-year-old woman with a Bismuth-Corlette type IIIB cholangiocarcinoma shows dilatation and crowding of left lobe biliary radicles (arrows) with an abrupt transition at the hilum (arrowhead) but no obvious mass. Type IIIB cholangiocarcinoma was confirmed with endoscopic retrograde cholangiography (ERC) and biopsy. <b>(c)</b> Multidetector CT scan obtained in a 67-year-old man with biopsy-proved cholangiocarcinoma shows a peripheral mass-forming lesion with delayed enhancement (arrowheads), ductal dilatation, and retraction of the liver surface. The CT appearances of cholangiocarcinomas vary depending on the anatomic location of the lesion relative to the biliary tree.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F4A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g04b.jpeg" height="1357" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4b.</b>  CT appearances of cholangiocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal reformatted CT image obtained in a 72-year-old woman shows an infiltrating intraductal extrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma causing irregular thickening and enhancement (white arrows) of the CBD with upstream dilatation of intrahepatic biliary radicles (black arrow). Inset shows a magnified view of the involved CBD (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Multidetector CT scan through the liver obtained in an 82-year-old woman with a Bismuth-Corlette type IIIB cholangiocarcinoma shows dilatation and crowding of left lobe biliary radicles (arrows) with an abrupt transition at the hilum (arrowhead) but no obvious mass. Type IIIB cholangiocarcinoma was confirmed with endoscopic retrograde cholangiography (ERC) and biopsy. <b>(c)</b> Multidetector CT scan obtained in a 67-year-old man with biopsy-proved cholangiocarcinoma shows a peripheral mass-forming lesion with delayed enhancement (arrowheads), ductal dilatation, and retraction of the liver surface. The CT appearances of cholangiocarcinomas vary depending on the anatomic location of the lesion relative to the biliary tree.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F4B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F4C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g04c.jpeg" height="1294" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F4C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 4c.</b>  CT appearances of cholangiocarcinoma. <b>(a)</b> Coronal reformatted CT image obtained in a 72-year-old woman shows an infiltrating intraductal extrahepatic cholangiocarcinoma causing irregular thickening and enhancement (white arrows) of the CBD with upstream dilatation of intrahepatic biliary radicles (black arrow). Inset shows a magnified view of the involved CBD (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Multidetector CT scan through the liver obtained in an 82-year-old woman with a Bismuth-Corlette type IIIB cholangiocarcinoma shows dilatation and crowding of left lobe biliary radicles (arrows) with an abrupt transition at the hilum (arrowhead) but no obvious mass. Type IIIB cholangiocarcinoma was confirmed with endoscopic retrograde cholangiography (ERC) and biopsy. <b>(c)</b> Multidetector CT scan obtained in a 67-year-old man with biopsy-proved cholangiocarcinoma shows a peripheral mass-forming lesion with delayed enhancement (arrowheads), ductal dilatation, and retraction of the liver surface. The CT appearances of cholangiocarcinomas vary depending on the anatomic location of the lesion relative to the biliary tree.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F4C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g05a.jpeg" height="1543" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5a.</b>  Peripheral mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 73-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Noncontrast multidetector CT scan obtained prior to contrast material administration shows an irregular hypoattenuating lesion in segments VII and VIII of the liver (arrows) with retraction of the posterior liver surface and atrophy of the right lobe. <b>(b)</b> On an arterial phase multidetector CT scan, the lesion is predominantly hypoattenuating with minimal peripheral enhancement posteriorly (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Delayed phase multidetector CT scan shows the lesion with peripheral enhancement (black arrows) and progressive enhancement posteriorly (white arrow), although the center of the lesion remains hypoattenuating (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F5A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g05b.jpeg" height="1373" width="1602" aria-labelledby="F5B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5b.</b>  Peripheral mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 73-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Noncontrast multidetector CT scan obtained prior to contrast material administration shows an irregular hypoattenuating lesion in segments VII and VIII of the liver (arrows) with retraction of the posterior liver surface and atrophy of the right lobe. <b>(b)</b> On an arterial phase multidetector CT scan, the lesion is predominantly hypoattenuating with minimal peripheral enhancement posteriorly (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Delayed phase multidetector CT scan shows the lesion with peripheral enhancement (black arrows) and progressive enhancement posteriorly (white arrow), although the center of the lesion remains hypoattenuating (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F5B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F5C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g05c.jpeg" height="1470" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F5C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 5c.</b>  Peripheral mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 73-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Noncontrast multidetector CT scan obtained prior to contrast material administration shows an irregular hypoattenuating lesion in segments VII and VIII of the liver (arrows) with retraction of the posterior liver surface and atrophy of the right lobe. <b>(b)</b> On an arterial phase multidetector CT scan, the lesion is predominantly hypoattenuating with minimal peripheral enhancement posteriorly (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Delayed phase multidetector CT scan shows the lesion with peripheral enhancement (black arrows) and progressive enhancement posteriorly (white arrow), although the center of the lesion remains hypoattenuating (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F5C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g06a.jpeg" height="1487" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6a.</b>  Peripheral cholangiocarcinoma in a 73-year-old man who was scheduled for surgery. Multidetector CT with CT angiography and CT venography was performed for preoperative evaluation. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a small, peripheral, heterogeneously enhancing mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in the right hepatic lobe (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal maximum-intensity-projection image from CT angiographic data obtained to map the vascular anatomy shows a replaced left hepatic artery arising from the left gastric artery (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Maximum-intensity-projection image from CT venographic data shows that the hepatic venous confluence is uninvolved by the tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F6A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g06b.jpeg" height="1487" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6b.</b>  Peripheral cholangiocarcinoma in a 73-year-old man who was scheduled for surgery. Multidetector CT with CT angiography and CT venography was performed for preoperative evaluation. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a small, peripheral, heterogeneously enhancing mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in the right hepatic lobe (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal maximum-intensity-projection image from CT angiographic data obtained to map the vascular anatomy shows a replaced left hepatic artery arising from the left gastric artery (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Maximum-intensity-projection image from CT venographic data shows that the hepatic venous confluence is uninvolved by the tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F6B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F6C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g06c.jpeg" height="1270" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F6C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 6c.</b>  Peripheral cholangiocarcinoma in a 73-year-old man who was scheduled for surgery. Multidetector CT with CT angiography and CT venography was performed for preoperative evaluation. <b>(a)</b> CT scan shows a small, peripheral, heterogeneously enhancing mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in the right hepatic lobe (arrow). <b>(b)</b> Coronal maximum-intensity-projection image from CT angiographic data obtained to map the vascular anatomy shows a replaced left hepatic artery arising from the left gastric artery (arrow). <b>(c)</b> Maximum-intensity-projection image from CT venographic data shows that the hepatic venous confluence is uninvolved by the tumor.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F6C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g07a.jpeg" height="1008" width="1332" aria-labelledby="F7A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7a.</b>  Klatskin tumor in a 57-year-old man who presented with jaundice, weight loss, and abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Multidetector CT scan shows dilatation of the intrahepatic biliary radicles in both hepatic lobes (black arrows) with an abrupt cutoff at the hilum (white arrow) but no discernible mass. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding coronal minimum-intensity-projection image shows the dilated biliary tree and obstruction by a hilar cholangiocarcinoma (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F7A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F7B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g07b.jpeg" height="1362" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F7B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 7b.</b>  Klatskin tumor in a 57-year-old man who presented with jaundice, weight loss, and abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Multidetector CT scan shows dilatation of the intrahepatic biliary radicles in both hepatic lobes (black arrows) with an abrupt cutoff at the hilum (white arrow) but no discernible mass. <b>(b)</b> Corresponding coronal minimum-intensity-projection image shows the dilated biliary tree and obstruction by a hilar cholangiocarcinoma (arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F7B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g08a.jpeg" height="1196" width="1710" aria-labelledby="F8A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8a.</b>  Mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 68-year-old man who presented with abdominal pain and jaundice. Contrast-enhanced multidetector CT scans through the liver show a heterogeneously enhancing mass in the left hepatic lobe (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) causing segmental biliary dilatation and atrophy of the left lobe, in conjunction with an enlarged lymph node in the gastrohepatic space (arrow in <b>a</b>) and peritoneal metastases (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F8A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F8B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g08b.jpeg" height="1259" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F8B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 8b.</b>  Mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 68-year-old man who presented with abdominal pain and jaundice. Contrast-enhanced multidetector CT scans through the liver show a heterogeneously enhancing mass in the left hepatic lobe (arrowheads in <b>a</b>) causing segmental biliary dilatation and atrophy of the left lobe, in conjunction with an enlarged lymph node in the gastrohepatic space (arrow in <b>a</b>) and peritoneal metastases (arrow in <b>b</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F8B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g09a.jpeg" height="1399" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9a.</b>  Mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 41-year-old man who presented with right upper quadrant discomfort. <b>(a)</b> Out-of-phase gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows a hypointense lobulated mass in the right hepatic lobe (arrows). <b>(b)</b> On a fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image, the mass appears hyperintense (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Early-phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows irregular peripheral enhancement of the mass (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Delayed phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows progressive heterogeneous enhancement of the lesion (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F9A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g09b.jpeg" height="1399" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9b.</b>  Mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 41-year-old man who presented with right upper quadrant discomfort. <b>(a)</b> Out-of-phase gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows a hypointense lobulated mass in the right hepatic lobe (arrows). <b>(b)</b> On a fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image, the mass appears hyperintense (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Early-phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows irregular peripheral enhancement of the mass (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Delayed phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows progressive heterogeneous enhancement of the lesion (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F9B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g09c.jpeg" height="1410" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9c.</b>  Mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 41-year-old man who presented with right upper quadrant discomfort. <b>(a)</b> Out-of-phase gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows a hypointense lobulated mass in the right hepatic lobe (arrows). <b>(b)</b> On a fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image, the mass appears hyperintense (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Early-phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows irregular peripheral enhancement of the mass (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Delayed phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows progressive heterogeneous enhancement of the lesion (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F9C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F9D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g09d.jpeg" height="1410" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F9D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 9d.</b>  Mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 41-year-old man who presented with right upper quadrant discomfort. <b>(a)</b> Out-of-phase gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows a hypointense lobulated mass in the right hepatic lobe (arrows). <b>(b)</b> On a fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image, the mass appears hyperintense (arrows). <b>(c)</b> Early-phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows irregular peripheral enhancement of the mass (arrows). <b>(d)</b> Delayed phase contrast-enhanced T1-weighted MR image shows progressive heterogeneous enhancement of the lesion (<b>*</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F9D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g10a.jpeg" height="1645" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10a.</b>  Bismuth-Corlette classification scheme for cholangiocarcinomas. MR cholangiograms were obtained in five different patients. Drawings of the lesions are shown in the corresponding insets (cf <a href="#F2">Fig 2</a>). Type I involves the CHD with abrupt cutoff of the RHD and LHD at the confluence (arrow in <b>a</b>); type II, the CHD (thick arrow in <b>b</b>) and the junction of the RHD and LHD (thin arrow in <b>b</b>); type IIIA, the CHD (arrow in <b>c</b>), biliary junction, and RHD (arrowheads in <b>c</b>); type IIIB, the CHD (arrow in <b>d</b>), biliary junction, and LHD (arrowhead in <b>d</b>); and type IV, the CHD (arrow in <b>e</b>) and the biliary junction, with extension to both the RHD and LHD (arrowheads in <b>e</b>) or a multifocal bile duct tumor. The Bismuth-Corlette classification scheme can help in planning the approach to and management of cholangiocarcinomas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F10A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g10b.jpeg" height="1645" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10b.</b>  Bismuth-Corlette classification scheme for cholangiocarcinomas. MR cholangiograms were obtained in five different patients. Drawings of the lesions are shown in the corresponding insets (cf <a href="#F2">Fig 2</a>). Type I involves the CHD with abrupt cutoff of the RHD and LHD at the confluence (arrow in <b>a</b>); type II, the CHD (thick arrow in <b>b</b>) and the junction of the RHD and LHD (thin arrow in <b>b</b>); type IIIA, the CHD (arrow in <b>c</b>), biliary junction, and RHD (arrowheads in <b>c</b>); type IIIB, the CHD (arrow in <b>d</b>), biliary junction, and LHD (arrowhead in <b>d</b>); and type IV, the CHD (arrow in <b>e</b>) and the biliary junction, with extension to both the RHD and LHD (arrowheads in <b>e</b>) or a multifocal bile duct tumor. The Bismuth-Corlette classification scheme can help in planning the approach to and management of cholangiocarcinomas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F10B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g10c.jpeg" height="1617" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10c.</b>  Bismuth-Corlette classification scheme for cholangiocarcinomas. MR cholangiograms were obtained in five different patients. Drawings of the lesions are shown in the corresponding insets (cf <a href="#F2">Fig 2</a>). Type I involves the CHD with abrupt cutoff of the RHD and LHD at the confluence (arrow in <b>a</b>); type II, the CHD (thick arrow in <b>b</b>) and the junction of the RHD and LHD (thin arrow in <b>b</b>); type IIIA, the CHD (arrow in <b>c</b>), biliary junction, and RHD (arrowheads in <b>c</b>); type IIIB, the CHD (arrow in <b>d</b>), biliary junction, and LHD (arrowhead in <b>d</b>); and type IV, the CHD (arrow in <b>e</b>) and the biliary junction, with extension to both the RHD and LHD (arrowheads in <b>e</b>) or a multifocal bile duct tumor. The Bismuth-Corlette classification scheme can help in planning the approach to and management of cholangiocarcinomas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F10C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g10d.jpeg" height="1617" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10d.</b>  Bismuth-Corlette classification scheme for cholangiocarcinomas. MR cholangiograms were obtained in five different patients. Drawings of the lesions are shown in the corresponding insets (cf <a href="#F2">Fig 2</a>). Type I involves the CHD with abrupt cutoff of the RHD and LHD at the confluence (arrow in <b>a</b>); type II, the CHD (thick arrow in <b>b</b>) and the junction of the RHD and LHD (thin arrow in <b>b</b>); type IIIA, the CHD (arrow in <b>c</b>), biliary junction, and RHD (arrowheads in <b>c</b>); type IIIB, the CHD (arrow in <b>d</b>), biliary junction, and LHD (arrowhead in <b>d</b>); and type IV, the CHD (arrow in <b>e</b>) and the biliary junction, with extension to both the RHD and LHD (arrowheads in <b>e</b>) or a multifocal bile duct tumor. The Bismuth-Corlette classification scheme can help in planning the approach to and management of cholangiocarcinomas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F10D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F10E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g10e.jpeg" height="1707" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F10E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 10e.</b>  Bismuth-Corlette classification scheme for cholangiocarcinomas. MR cholangiograms were obtained in five different patients. Drawings of the lesions are shown in the corresponding insets (cf <a href="#F2">Fig 2</a>). Type I involves the CHD with abrupt cutoff of the RHD and LHD at the confluence (arrow in <b>a</b>); type II, the CHD (thick arrow in <b>b</b>) and the junction of the RHD and LHD (thin arrow in <b>b</b>); type IIIA, the CHD (arrow in <b>c</b>), biliary junction, and RHD (arrowheads in <b>c</b>); type IIIB, the CHD (arrow in <b>d</b>), biliary junction, and LHD (arrowhead in <b>d</b>); and type IV, the CHD (arrow in <b>e</b>) and the biliary junction, with extension to both the RHD and LHD (arrowheads in <b>e</b>) or a multifocal bile duct tumor. The Bismuth-Corlette classification scheme can help in planning the approach to and management of cholangiocarcinomas.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F10E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g11a.jpeg" height="1247" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11a.</b>  Mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 41-year-old man with jaundice and altered liver function. <b>(a)</b> Fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense mass in the left hepatic lobe and extending to the porta hepatis (arrow), with dilatation of the biliary radicles in both lobes (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Out-of-phase gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows the mass encasing the left portal vein (arrow) and extending to the porta hepatis. <b>(c, d)</b> Corresponding contrast-enhanced MR angiograms show encasement of the left hepatic artery (arrow in <b>c</b>) and invasion and nonvisualization of the left portal vein (arrow in <b>d</b>), which prohibited surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F11A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g11b.jpeg" height="1247" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11b.</b>  Mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 41-year-old man with jaundice and altered liver function. <b>(a)</b> Fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense mass in the left hepatic lobe and extending to the porta hepatis (arrow), with dilatation of the biliary radicles in both lobes (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Out-of-phase gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows the mass encasing the left portal vein (arrow) and extending to the porta hepatis. <b>(c, d)</b> Corresponding contrast-enhanced MR angiograms show encasement of the left hepatic artery (arrow in <b>c</b>) and invasion and nonvisualization of the left portal vein (arrow in <b>d</b>), which prohibited surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F11B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g11c.jpeg" height="1251" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11c.</b>  Mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 41-year-old man with jaundice and altered liver function. <b>(a)</b> Fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense mass in the left hepatic lobe and extending to the porta hepatis (arrow), with dilatation of the biliary radicles in both lobes (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Out-of-phase gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows the mass encasing the left portal vein (arrow) and extending to the porta hepatis. <b>(c, d)</b> Corresponding contrast-enhanced MR angiograms show encasement of the left hepatic artery (arrow in <b>c</b>) and invasion and nonvisualization of the left portal vein (arrow in <b>d</b>), which prohibited surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F11C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F11D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g11d.jpeg" height="1251" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F11D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 11d.</b>  Mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 41-year-old man with jaundice and altered liver function. <b>(a)</b> Fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image shows a hyperintense mass in the left hepatic lobe and extending to the porta hepatis (arrow), with dilatation of the biliary radicles in both lobes (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> Out-of-phase gradient-echo T1-weighted MR image shows the mass encasing the left portal vein (arrow) and extending to the porta hepatis. <b>(c, d)</b> Corresponding contrast-enhanced MR angiograms show encasement of the left hepatic artery (arrow in <b>c</b>) and invasion and nonvisualization of the left portal vein (arrow in <b>d</b>), which prohibited surgery.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F11D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g12a.jpeg" height="1230" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12a.</b>  Mass-forming peripheral cholangiocarcinoma in a 72-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image obtained after the intravenous administration of gadolinium-based contrast material shows a heterogeneously enhancing lesion (arrows). <b>(b)</b> On a fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image obtained after the administration of manganese dipyridoxylethylenediamine diacetate bisphosphate, the lesion (arrows) appears hypointense relative to the enhancing liver. The use of this contrast agent increases lesion-liver contrast and lesion conspicuity.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F12A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F12B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g12b.jpeg" height="1230" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F12B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 12b.</b>  Mass-forming peripheral cholangiocarcinoma in a 72-year-old woman. <b>(a)</b> Fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image obtained after the intravenous administration of gadolinium-based contrast material shows a heterogeneously enhancing lesion (arrows). <b>(b)</b> On a fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image obtained after the administration of manganese dipyridoxylethylenediamine diacetate bisphosphate, the lesion (arrows) appears hypointense relative to the enhancing liver. The use of this contrast agent increases lesion-liver contrast and lesion conspicuity.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F12B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g13a.jpeg" height="1405" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13a.</b>  Intraductal infiltrating cholangiocarcinoma of the proximal CBD in a 66-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Delayed phase contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows enhancement of the cholangiocarcinoma (arrow). <b>(b)</b> On a diffusion-weighted image obtained at the same level, the lesion (arrow) is hyperintense with restricted diffusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F13A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F13B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g13b.jpeg" height="1405" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F13B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 13b.</b>  Intraductal infiltrating cholangiocarcinoma of the proximal CBD in a 66-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Delayed phase contrast-enhanced fat-saturated T1-weighted MR image shows enhancement of the cholangiocarcinoma (arrow). <b>(b)</b> On a diffusion-weighted image obtained at the same level, the lesion (arrow) is hyperintense with restricted diffusion.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F13B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g14a.jpeg" height="1542" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14a.</b>  Hilar cholangiocarcinoma in a 62-year-old man who presented with jaundice and abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image through the liver reveal a mass at the hilum (arrow) with dilatation of the intrahepatic biliary radicles (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> FDG PET scan through the hilum (arrow) does not show increased activity. The lesion proved to be a cholangiocarcinoma at histopathologic analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F14A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F14B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g14b.jpeg" height="1542" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F14B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 14b.</b>  Hilar cholangiocarcinoma in a 62-year-old man who presented with jaundice and abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Coronal fat-saturated T2-weighted MR image through the liver reveal a mass at the hilum (arrow) with dilatation of the intrahepatic biliary radicles (arrowheads). <b>(b)</b> FDG PET scan through the hilum (arrow) does not show increased activity. The lesion proved to be a cholangiocarcinoma at histopathologic analysis.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F14B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g15a.jpeg" height="1389" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F15A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15a.</b>  Mass-forming peripheral cholangiocarcinoma in a 39-year-old woman who presented with abdominal pain, jaundice, and weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Noncontrast multidetector CT scan shows an ill-defined, hypoattenuating mass in the left hepatic lobe (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Noncontrast multidetector CT scan shows bulky adenopathy at the porta hepatis (arrowheads). Note also the pneumobilia, which resulted from an endoscopic procedure performed to relieve the obstruction. <b>(c, d)</b> Corresponding fused FDG PET/CT images reveal increased FDG uptake in the lesion (arrows in <b>c</b>) and in the portal nodes (arrowheads in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F15A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g15b.jpeg" height="1389" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F15B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15b.</b>  Mass-forming peripheral cholangiocarcinoma in a 39-year-old woman who presented with abdominal pain, jaundice, and weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Noncontrast multidetector CT scan shows an ill-defined, hypoattenuating mass in the left hepatic lobe (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Noncontrast multidetector CT scan shows bulky adenopathy at the porta hepatis (arrowheads). Note also the pneumobilia, which resulted from an endoscopic procedure performed to relieve the obstruction. <b>(c, d)</b> Corresponding fused FDG PET/CT images reveal increased FDG uptake in the lesion (arrows in <b>c</b>) and in the portal nodes (arrowheads in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F15B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19c15c.jpeg" height="988" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F15C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15c.</b>  Mass-forming peripheral cholangiocarcinoma in a 39-year-old woman who presented with abdominal pain, jaundice, and weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Noncontrast multidetector CT scan shows an ill-defined, hypoattenuating mass in the left hepatic lobe (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Noncontrast multidetector CT scan shows bulky adenopathy at the porta hepatis (arrowheads). Note also the pneumobilia, which resulted from an endoscopic procedure performed to relieve the obstruction. <b>(c, d)</b> Corresponding fused FDG PET/CT images reveal increased FDG uptake in the lesion (arrows in <b>c</b>) and in the portal nodes (arrowheads in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F15C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F15D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19c15d.jpeg" height="988" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F15D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 15d.</b>  Mass-forming peripheral cholangiocarcinoma in a 39-year-old woman who presented with abdominal pain, jaundice, and weight loss. <b>(a)</b> Noncontrast multidetector CT scan shows an ill-defined, hypoattenuating mass in the left hepatic lobe (arrows). <b>(b)</b> Noncontrast multidetector CT scan shows bulky adenopathy at the porta hepatis (arrowheads). Note also the pneumobilia, which resulted from an endoscopic procedure performed to relieve the obstruction. <b>(c, d)</b> Corresponding fused FDG PET/CT images reveal increased FDG uptake in the lesion (arrows in <b>c</b>) and in the portal nodes (arrowheads in <b>d</b>).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F15D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g16a.jpeg" height="1411" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16a.</b>  Metastatic inoperable cholangiocarcinoma in a 66-year-old woman who presented with abdominal pain and jaundice. <b>(a)</b> FDG PET scan shows increased uptake in a mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in the left hepatic lobe (arrow) and in liver metastases (arrowheads), findings that prohibited surgery. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up FDG PET scan obtained after 2 months of gemcitabineavastin therapy shows significantly reduced uptake in all the lesions, findings that signify a good response.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F16A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F16B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g16b.jpeg" height="1368" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F16B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 16b.</b>  Metastatic inoperable cholangiocarcinoma in a 66-year-old woman who presented with abdominal pain and jaundice. <b>(a)</b> FDG PET scan shows increased uptake in a mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in the left hepatic lobe (arrow) and in liver metastases (arrowheads), findings that prohibited surgery. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up FDG PET scan obtained after 2 months of gemcitabineavastin therapy shows significantly reduced uptake in all the lesions, findings that signify a good response.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F16B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g17a.jpeg" height="1545" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F17A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17a.</b>  Intraductal cholangiocarcinoma in a 56-year-old woman with PSC. <b>(a)</b> Coronal FDG PET scan shows increased uptake in an extrahepatic malignant biliary stricture (cholangiocarcinoma) (thin arrow). However, increased uptake is also seen in intrahepatic benign strictures (thick arrow). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding ERC image shows a long extrahepatic stricture (thin arrow), which was confirmed to be malignant at biopsy, and a beaded appearance of the right intrahepatic duct due to multiple benign strictures (thick arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F17A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F17B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g17b.jpeg" height="1606" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F17B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 17b.</b>  Intraductal cholangiocarcinoma in a 56-year-old woman with PSC. <b>(a)</b> Coronal FDG PET scan shows increased uptake in an extrahepatic malignant biliary stricture (cholangiocarcinoma) (thin arrow). However, increased uptake is also seen in intrahepatic benign strictures (thick arrow). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding ERC image shows a long extrahepatic stricture (thin arrow), which was confirmed to be malignant at biopsy, and a beaded appearance of the right intrahepatic duct due to multiple benign strictures (thick arrow).<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F17B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g18a.jpeg" height="1279" width="1584" aria-labelledby="F18A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18a.</b>  Small, biopsy-proved mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 73-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Multidetector CT scan through the liver shows a small, hypoattenuating mass (arrow). Surgical resection was considered. <b>(b)</b> CT volumetric image obtained before portal vein embolization shows the left hepatic lobe with a volume of 955 mL. <b>(c)</b> CT scan shows the site of right portal vein embolization (arrow). <b>(d)</b> CT volumetric image shows the left hepatic lobe with an increased volume of 1133 mL. <b>(e)</b> CT scan obtained after right hepatic lobectomy shows the liver with sufficient functional residual volume.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F18A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g18b.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F18B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18b.</b>  Small, biopsy-proved mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 73-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Multidetector CT scan through the liver shows a small, hypoattenuating mass (arrow). Surgical resection was considered. <b>(b)</b> CT volumetric image obtained before portal vein embolization shows the left hepatic lobe with a volume of 955 mL. <b>(c)</b> CT scan shows the site of right portal vein embolization (arrow). <b>(d)</b> CT volumetric image shows the left hepatic lobe with an increased volume of 1133 mL. <b>(e)</b> CT scan obtained after right hepatic lobectomy shows the liver with sufficient functional residual volume.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F18B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g18c.jpeg" height="1162" width="1440" aria-labelledby="F18C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18c.</b>  Small, biopsy-proved mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 73-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Multidetector CT scan through the liver shows a small, hypoattenuating mass (arrow). Surgical resection was considered. <b>(b)</b> CT volumetric image obtained before portal vein embolization shows the left hepatic lobe with a volume of 955 mL. <b>(c)</b> CT scan shows the site of right portal vein embolization (arrow). <b>(d)</b> CT volumetric image shows the left hepatic lobe with an increased volume of 1133 mL. <b>(e)</b> CT scan obtained after right hepatic lobectomy shows the liver with sufficient functional residual volume.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F18C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g18d.jpeg" height="1352" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F18D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18d.</b>  Small, biopsy-proved mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 73-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Multidetector CT scan through the liver shows a small, hypoattenuating mass (arrow). Surgical resection was considered. <b>(b)</b> CT volumetric image obtained before portal vein embolization shows the left hepatic lobe with a volume of 955 mL. <b>(c)</b> CT scan shows the site of right portal vein embolization (arrow). <b>(d)</b> CT volumetric image shows the left hepatic lobe with an increased volume of 1133 mL. <b>(e)</b> CT scan obtained after right hepatic lobectomy shows the liver with sufficient functional residual volume.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F18D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F18E" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g18e.jpeg" height="1237" width="1566" aria-labelledby="F18E" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 18e.</b>  Small, biopsy-proved mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in a 73-year-old man. <b>(a)</b> Multidetector CT scan through the liver shows a small, hypoattenuating mass (arrow). Surgical resection was considered. <b>(b)</b> CT volumetric image obtained before portal vein embolization shows the left hepatic lobe with a volume of 955 mL. <b>(c)</b> CT scan shows the site of right portal vein embolization (arrow). <b>(d)</b> CT volumetric image shows the left hepatic lobe with an increased volume of 1133 mL. <b>(e)</b> CT scan obtained after right hepatic lobectomy shows the liver with sufficient functional residual volume.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F18E">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19c19a.jpeg" height="993" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F19A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19a.</b>  Mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in segment IV of the liver in a 73-year-old woman. On coronal subtracted images from dynamic contrast-enhanced 3D fat-saturated gradient-echo MR imaging data obtained before <b>(a)</b> and 6 weeks after <b>(b)</b> the initiation of antiangiogenic drug treatment, the cholangiocarcinoma demonstrates peripheral heterogeneous enhancement. The tumor has been outlined to indicate a region of interest for the calculation of vascularization parameters. The decrease in tumor vascularization after antiangiogenic drug administration, seen in <b>b</b>, was confirmed with transfer constant and extracellular volume fraction calculations.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F19A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F19B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19c19b.jpeg" height="993" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F19B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 19b.</b>  Mass-forming cholangiocarcinoma in segment IV of the liver in a 73-year-old woman. On coronal subtracted images from dynamic contrast-enhanced 3D fat-saturated gradient-echo MR imaging data obtained before <b>(a)</b> and 6 weeks after <b>(b)</b> the initiation of antiangiogenic drug treatment, the cholangiocarcinoma demonstrates peripheral heterogeneous enhancement. The tumor has been outlined to indicate a region of interest for the calculation of vascularization parameters. The decrease in tumor vascularization after antiangiogenic drug administration, seen in <b>b</b>, was confirmed with transfer constant and extracellular volume fraction calculations.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F19B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19c20a.jpeg" height="933" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F20A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20a.</b>  Pretreatment (<sup>90</sup>Y) images obtained in a 63-year-old woman with an inoperable peripheral cholangiocarcinoma who presented with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced multidetector CT scan shows the region of interest (outlined), which delineates the tumor and tumor volume (40 mL). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding FDG PET scan shows increased peripheral activity (arrows) but no extrahepatic disease. <b>(c)</b> Pretreatment visceral angiogram shows the coil (arrow) that was used to embolize the right gastric artery arising from the left hepatic artery. <b>(d)</b> SPECT image obtained after the injection of <sup>99m</sup>Tc macroaggregated albumin shows no extrahepatic shunt.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F20A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g20b.jpeg" height="1313" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F20B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20b.</b>  Pretreatment (<sup>90</sup>Y) images obtained in a 63-year-old woman with an inoperable peripheral cholangiocarcinoma who presented with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced multidetector CT scan shows the region of interest (outlined), which delineates the tumor and tumor volume (40 mL). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding FDG PET scan shows increased peripheral activity (arrows) but no extrahepatic disease. <b>(c)</b> Pretreatment visceral angiogram shows the coil (arrow) that was used to embolize the right gastric artery arising from the left hepatic artery. <b>(d)</b> SPECT image obtained after the injection of <sup>99m</sup>Tc macroaggregated albumin shows no extrahepatic shunt.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F20B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g20c.jpeg" height="1338" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F20C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20c.</b>  Pretreatment (<sup>90</sup>Y) images obtained in a 63-year-old woman with an inoperable peripheral cholangiocarcinoma who presented with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced multidetector CT scan shows the region of interest (outlined), which delineates the tumor and tumor volume (40 mL). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding FDG PET scan shows increased peripheral activity (arrows) but no extrahepatic disease. <b>(c)</b> Pretreatment visceral angiogram shows the coil (arrow) that was used to embolize the right gastric artery arising from the left hepatic artery. <b>(d)</b> SPECT image obtained after the injection of <sup>99m</sup>Tc macroaggregated albumin shows no extrahepatic shunt.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F20C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F20D" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g20d.jpeg" height="1338" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F20D" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 20d.</b>  Pretreatment (<sup>90</sup>Y) images obtained in a 63-year-old woman with an inoperable peripheral cholangiocarcinoma who presented with abdominal pain. <b>(a)</b> Contrast-enhanced multidetector CT scan shows the region of interest (outlined), which delineates the tumor and tumor volume (40 mL). <b>(b)</b> Corresponding FDG PET scan shows increased peripheral activity (arrows) but no extrahepatic disease. <b>(c)</b> Pretreatment visceral angiogram shows the coil (arrow) that was used to embolize the right gastric artery arising from the left hepatic artery. <b>(d)</b> SPECT image obtained after the injection of <sup>99m</sup>Tc macroaggregated albumin shows no extrahepatic shunt.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F20D">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21A" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g21a.jpeg" height="1538" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F21A" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21a.</b>  Posttreatment (<sup>90</sup>Y) images obtained in the same patient as in <a href="#F20A">Figure 20</a>. <b>(a)</b> SPECT image obtained after the selective injection of a calculated dose (1.23 MBq [33.24 μCi]) of internal radiation spheres shows the distribution of <sup>90</sup>Y in the liver. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up contrast-enhanced multidetector CT scan obtained 6 weeks later shows a decrease in tumor volume (29 mL) as depicted by the region of interest (outlined) (cf <a href="#F20A">Fig 20</a>). <b>(c)</b> PET scan shows that activity in the tumor has also decreased (arrows) compared with the pretreatment examination, a finding that suggests a response to treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F21A">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21B" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19c21b.jpeg" height="956" width="1280" aria-labelledby="F21B" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21b.</b>  Posttreatment (<sup>90</sup>Y) images obtained in the same patient as in <a href="#F20A">Figure 20</a>. <b>(a)</b> SPECT image obtained after the selective injection of a calculated dose (1.23 MBq [33.24 μCi]) of internal radiation spheres shows the distribution of <sup>90</sup>Y in the liver. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up contrast-enhanced multidetector CT scan obtained 6 weeks later shows a decrease in tumor volume (29 mL) as depicted by the region of interest (outlined) (cf <a href="#F20A">Fig 20</a>). <b>(c)</b> PET scan shows that activity in the tumor has also decreased (arrows) compared with the pretreatment examination, a finding that suggests a response to treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F21B">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F21C" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19g21c.jpeg" height="1350" width="1800" aria-labelledby="F21C" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 21c.</b>  Posttreatment (<sup>90</sup>Y) images obtained in the same patient as in <a href="#F20A">Figure 20</a>. <b>(a)</b> SPECT image obtained after the selective injection of a calculated dose (1.23 MBq [33.24 μCi]) of internal radiation spheres shows the distribution of <sup>90</sup>Y in the liver. <b>(b)</b> Follow-up contrast-enhanced multidetector CT scan obtained 6 weeks later shows a decrease in tumor volume (29 mL) as depicted by the region of interest (outlined) (cf <a href="#F20A">Fig 20</a>). <b>(c)</b> PET scan shows that activity in the tumor has also decreased (arrows) compared with the pretreatment examination, a finding that suggests a response to treatment.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F21C">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="F22" class="graphic"><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19l22x.jpeg" height="1280" width="1154" aria-labelledby="F22" loading="lazy" /><figcaption><b>Figure 22.</b>  Diagram illustrates a suggested algorithm for the diagnosis and treatment of cholangiocarcinomas. <i>CTA</i> = CT angiography, <i>CTP</i> = CT portography, <i>CTV</i> = CT venography, <i>DSA</i> = digital subtraction angiography, <i>EUS</i> = endoscopic US, <i>IHBR</i> = intrahepatic biliary radicles, <i>MDCT</i> = multidetector CT, <i>MRA</i> = MR angiography, <i>MRC</i> = MR cholangiography, <i>MRCP</i> = MR cholangiopancreatography, <i>MRP</i> = MR portography, <i>MRV</i> = MR venography, <i>PVE</i> = portal vein embolization, <i>RF</i> = radiofrequency, <i>USG</i> = US-guided.<div class="core-figure-tools"><ul><li><a class="core-figure-download-powerpoint" href="/action/downloadFigures?doi=10.1148%2Frg.285075183&amp;id=F22">Download as PowerPoint</a></li></ul></div></figcaption></figure></div></section><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T1" class="table"><figcaption><b>Table 1.</b> <b>Multidetector Computed Tomographic (CT) Features of Various Cholangiocarcinomas Surgical Treatment Options</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19t01x.jpeg" height="1082" width="1710" aria-labelledby="T1" loading="lazy" /></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T2" class="table"><figcaption><b>Table 2.</b> <b>Effectiveness of Helical CT in Determining Tumor Unresectability</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19t02x.jpeg" height="680" width="1800" aria-labelledby="T2" loading="lazy" /></figure></div><div class="figure-wrap"><figure id="T3" class="table"><figcaption><b>Table 3.</b> <b>MR Angiography versus Digital Subtraction Angiography in the Evaluation of Vascular</b></figcaption><img src="/cms/10.1148/rg.285075183/asset/images/g08se19t03x.jpeg" height="522" width="1800" aria-labelledby="T3" loading="lazy" /></figure></div><section id="bibliography" role="doc-bibliography"><h2>References</h2><div role="list"><div role="listitem" data-has="label"><div class="label">1.</div><div id="R1" class="citations"><div class="citation"><div class="citation-content"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-firstauthor"><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-snm">Singh</span><span class="named-content" data-type="arthw-fnm">P</span></span>, Patel T. Advances in the diagnosis, evaluation and management of cholangiocarcinoma. <em>Curr Opin Gastroenterol</em>2006; 22: 294–299.</div><div class="external-links"><div class="core-xlink-crossref"><a href="https://doi.org/10.1097/01.mog.0000218967.60633.64">Crossre